benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/cache/accounts/{accountId} - Invalidates Caches per account level

covered: DELETE Method - Valid Deletion: TC01 covers successful invalidation for a valid account.
DELETE Method - Non-Existent Resource: TC02, TC16, TC18 cover non-existent or partially populated scenarios.
DELETE Method - Invalid accountId formats: TC03, TC12, TC14, TC15 cover invalid formats and security-related inputs.
DELETE Method - Missing accountId in path: TC04 tests handling of missing path parameter.
Authorization - Authentication required: TC05 and TC06 cover authentication failures (401).
System health/availability: TC07 (degraded performance) and TC08 (dependent service unavailable) cover resilience scenarios.
Query Parameters / Extra parameters: TC09 verifies behavior with extra query params.
HTTP Method handling: TC11 covers unsupported methods (405).
Concurrency / Performance: TC13 covers concurrent requests and TC17/TC19 cover resilience and backward compatibility.
Edge cases: TC16 (no accounts), TC18 (partially populated), TC17 (transient network recovery), TC19 (backward compatibility).
Security: TC14 (SQL injection), TC15 (XSS) test input sanitization.
gaps: Authorization coverage gap: No explicit test ensuring 403 Forbidden for authenticated but unauthorized roles or scopes.
Rate limiting / throttling: No tests validating behavior under high request load within a short time window.
Caching headers: No tests validating caching headers (e.g., ETag, Cache-Control) or cache-related metadata.
Soft delete behavior: If applicable, no explicit test confirming soft-delete semantics versus hard delete.
Pagination not applicable here due to single-resource focus, but no explicit note on behavior with large scales beyond concurrency tests.
recommendations: Add a test ensuring a user with valid admin credentials but insufficient permissions receives 403 Forbidden when attempting the delete.
Introduce rate-limiting tests to verify proper handling of bursts or repeated requests (e.g., 429 or throttling behavior).
Add tests asserting presence and correctness of caching headers (ETag/Cache-Control) on DELETE responses, if applicable.
If the API supports soft-delete semantics, add tests to confirm deletion state vs. permanent removal.
